Addictive and fun! I'm now on my 2nd playthrough (Insane difficulty). Based on the name I thought this would be a TD game, but the battle screen is simple: hordes of enemies attack, with you and your mercenary allies defending. Graphics are low-res (8-bit/pixelated), but so what, as you level up it's fun to watch the chaos and destruction that you rain down on enemies. Item mods and skill trees are really deep! Menus are OK but could be better. There isn't much help on how to play (let alone play well), not even at the wiki website, but that isn't necessary, just jump in and play: the basics are easy, and you can figure out the advanced concepts as you go along. During my first playthrough (on Normal -- you probably shouldn't bother with Easy) I realized I should be Enhancing and Modding my weapons. I'm sure there's other stuff I could be doing (or doing better) but that's OK. Right now I still enjoy grinding the normal battles, but the most fun for me is the "Tower of Trial" levels which have unique enemies, and some require puzzle solving to complete. A note on IAP: it's there, but the developer actually discourages you from it, and that's not disingenuous because I haven't once felt the need. I'm sure he'll be happy to take your money if you are in a hurry to convert the game into an idle game (which can be gradually done through grinding), or climb the leaderboards, but neither of those aspects is important to me. Conclusion: 5 stars, game is worth more than its price.

If you like games where you can upgrade run after run and get further on higher and higher difficulties, do yourself a favor and download this.  Dungeon Defense: Invasion of Heroes is an unassuming game. At first glance, it's overwhelming the number of options that are available, but the more you play, the more fun it becomes. I am a big fan of idle and incremental games, and I make a point to try out as many as I can. This is one of the best incremental games I've found: I have been running this game continuously for almost a week, cycling out battery packs to keep it charged. It's that good.  The more you play, the more options open up to you and the more you get hooked. If you have any questions, contact me on twitter (@morjax), and I'll try to help. Also check out the google plus group for the game since the wiki is lacking in detail. There's a LOT to this game.

A pixel-art, simplified defense game with semi-idle elements. You face waves of enemies that are easily dispatched. Good as a time killer, and easy on the purse, but ultimately average.

I had no idea what I was getting myself into when I tried out Dungeon Defender. As the name implies, I’m defending a dungeon… but how am I defending it? Am I building walls, a maze… will I need to execute some crazy real time strategy maneuvers? ….Nope.  You do buy upgrades, and then you play against several waves from hordes of heroes trying to break down the front gate and steal treasure from my dungeon!  There’s actually a great deal of depth in Dungeon Defender. You need to manage a squad of NPC’s whom help defend your dungeon from high onto of the walls.  You gear them, enchant their gear, and use their special powers which are on cool downs.  You also purchase passive upgrades by “building/purchasing structures” which may decrease research time, increase exp gained, increase gold gamed per turn, etc.  You research technology which will improve your allies damage, there are special challenges to keep the player engaged… there are unlockables with premium currency… different difficulties, a type of “ascension” feature that resets your game and gives you a special currency, and some very annoying google Play Games achievements which will require me to play for a long time.

As for most everything in the game, its very creative, fun, is very 
visually interesting, and with each time you play it leaves you wanting to 
try out different playstyles with different characters, giving amazing 
replayability. The concepts out of game, such as research, weapon mods, the 
item store, etc. are not outlined very well, but by searching around and 
clicking different things you can easily learn about them, so in a way it 
is far better than holding your hand through a long and tiresome tutorial, 
making it an excellent game to just jump into. The rounds are pretty short, 
so its quite easy to play round after round in a matter of a few minutes. 
Overall its very well made, is very fun, keeps you playing on round after 
round, and hits it out of the park in almost every category. My only 
entirely negative thoughts are the skills used in games arent really 
explained, leaving the player to just try and figure out what they do. But 
this is a very minor point and doesnt at all affect my opinion that this 
app is worth every cent and then some.

developers who don't know what they're doing, but this succeeds. It is 
compact, battery-light, and sports charming music that is well composed to 
add flavor with that type of sound. Gameplay is easy to pick up and there 
are explanations at every point in the game so you don't forget, though it 
may be a little difficult to understand at first. Not that it matters, 
since the game starts easy anyways. The reincarnation aspect seems to 
suggest valuable replay as well. It's easy to drop in for a few minutes 
because each level is short, so there is no time commitment necessary. 
Overall I would play this for some time.

I don't usually rate games, especially those that ask me to rate them in 
game, but this is a fantastic little wave defender game that's surprisingly 
deep. Upon first glance the menus may seem a bit overbearing but you'll 
quickly figure out what every tab and button does from a little just 
exploring said menus. The music isn't exactly varied, but is pretty good 
and the retro graphics make what's going on clear, which is more than what 
can be said about many of these types of games, but these aspects aren't 
super important in the grand scheme of things. This game is all about the 
systems. So, if you enjoy min/maxing stats, being able to customize your 
roster, and upgrading all the while getting an ever-present sense of 
enjoyment from seeing progression, you'll love this game.

A really fun RPG stat management game. The actual combat game play is a bit 
simple but if you enjoy very long term RPG, progress management style games 
then you'll love this. Simple enough to enjoy for new players but once you 
start to realise the depth of the games rebirth system, you quickly realise 
this is a game designed to last for a very long time, where your decisions 
tend to have very long lasting impacts which are quite hidden from you. 
Some will like this, some may be put off. The only part that makes me think 
I won't play the game as long as some of its fans is the fact that it's a 
thing that you can unlock features that automate almost everything. That 
just screams "the grind is strong with this one". Still, it's fun. Great 
way to pass a lot of time.

A very cunning game for sucking money from your wallet. At first it looks like an RPG defense game, but after you've invested time in it you realise it's an idle game behind a paywall. Either you pay $35.50 (preferably $93 for a big speed boost and removal of the last annoyances), or you have to manually grind for a very long time before the game becomes a proper idle game. There are some minor presentation bugs, e.g. if there are more than 3 mutations, the last one isn't named on the battle screen; the note days "The dungeon walls regenerated itself" even when they were undamaged. That's also an example of how the English translation could do with improvement.

Why is this masterpiece for free right now?! I mean, come on. After all those clicker games and tower defence, rpgs, I thought that this game is not gonna capture my attention for more than 2 hours. But guess what, it did. Yes it's still has those core elements of clicker game, where you go up and up, upgrades get slower, and then you reset and start everything again with a bonus, so I quit. But before I doing that I had a lot of fun.

The game had a slightly difficult learning curve. It's not really hard mechanically, it's just a bit rough getting the hang of what to buy, when to buy it, and how to navigate the menus. Other than that, the core gameplay loop is very compelling, and the mid-long term rewards come frequently enough to keep me entertained. Good stuff overall!

While searching for something new I discovered this game, which at the time said it was discounted from 99 cents to free, so I downloaded it. At first I was a bit confused but I quickly realized that it only meant that there would be a lot to do and a lot to learn. Two important features games need to keep me entertained. For what it was worth to me I decided to buy like 20 dollars worth of "pay to win" type stuff. This game is in NO WAY PAY TO WIN, but it was worth it to me. Game play is basically stationary shooter with a TON of potential for growth through item enhancing/skill leveling/character and stat unlocks/massively increasing difficulties with increasing rewards. Worth a dollar in my opinion and worth more if you have the means to support a small game developer with a surprise gem on the Google play store.

Lots of itty-bitty pixelly nuggetty goodness, with loot and RPG elements.  It's much like an old JRPG, where you've got your whole team on one side of the screen. The difference is, you point and click at approaching enemies, like "Missile Command" played sideways. You frenetically click till there's no-one left, and then you can choose your new level-up skills: useful battlefield abilities. You can also sort through all the shiny new loot, and equip the good stuff for your favourite characters, and choose what skills they should focus on, and more.   It's so simple, yet deep. Retro elegance. The developer nailed it.

So even though I'd backed up my saves, I can't use them and therefore I have had to start again. Uninstalled. This is a massive screw up by the developer in this regard. Other than the major, major save issues, this game has nice artwork, cool music, no annoying advertisements (which also means it's safe to play outside so you don't risk mobile data costs) and lots of depth of progression. Other criticisms are that there needs to be better explanations of some of the certain level up skills, some sound incredibly similar to each other. Other things, scalable UI for larger screens and some text fixes are required. Maybe a little more optimisation for menu layout and loot handling at the end of a round, but that's far from being a real issue.

Best paid game available, definitely worth $0.99, although I think it could go for a $5 game if it wanted to. Updates always bring improvements, however, there are still some spelling and grammar errors, but they are surprisingly rare for how much text there is in the game. The game is challenging and long, getting strong enough for the Hell difficulties seems impossible, but there are quite a few upgrades in the game, some easier to obtain than others (Rubies are an excruciating grind), but I suppose you can get all of them and they would add up to being strong enough for the Hell modes. I can tell you right now though, if you like the game Defender, long games, upgrade games, and prestige games, this will be one of the best Android games you can get. Only one issue I'm having is that the game size grows as you play it. Meaning, it starts at 69MB on your SD card, then can grow as big as 21GB (it did for me, but it somehow still functioned normally AFTER exceeding my max space, though with noticeable slow down to my phone. The thing is though, looking at your storage capacity says it's all normal, holding at 2.5GB for me, even though the app info says 21GB). I think the cause for this is that after every day you beat, the game automatically saves. Considering you will probably be going as far as 1000 days, you'll definitely be saving a LOT. So I think the issue is that it saves a new file every day, but it does not erase those saves it made, ever. So those saves are all cached somewhere, with no way to delete them. I had to clear the data from the app to fix this problem. The good news is that there's cloud save, so no damage done. May just be a specific "me" issue anyway, though. Awesome game though.

The game is split into two parts. The fight and the preparation.   The fight is simple. You tap and the main character shoots. You hire mercenaries and the mercenaries shoot. You (+mercenaries) defend a dungeon (reason for the title: Dungeon Defense). The battle is split into rounds. One round has a hoard of weak enemies, and a somewhat stronger "boss" at some point. At the end of the rounds, you gain equipment and experience (dependant on how much enemies you defeated). And if you level up, you level up a skill, which is there for you in the next Battle.   The preparation is complicated; it's split into six tabs.   1) The Notebook. To save.   2) The Team. To hire mercenaries and change the order of the team.   3) The Equipment. To shop and to sell accessories and equipment.   4) The Dungeon. To upgrade various parts of the game, and has an immediate effect.   5) The Laboratory. To upgrade various parts of the game, and has no immediate effect.   6) The Battle. To start the fight section of the game.   All I did was cover the basic function of the tabs because the game covers a lot more complicated functions which I don't want to go into. But, I think the reason the game is more complex compared to the explanations above, are due to two reasons.   First, the design. The game separates it's functions into boxes, and it's boring. There are boxes in boxes on a phone, which is a rectangular box. It's good to know the options sub-options, but there's got to be a less confusing design. Example, change the shapes. It's an easier time navigating the equipment function if purchasing are circles and selling are triangles. Or if it's uniqueness you want, add aesthetics. Example, create characters. It would be cool to see a merchant or spelunker who trades with you.   Second, the colors. The background is black, and like the design, it's boring. I understand you want to keep the theme of dark (because it's a dungeon), but I think there are other methods of making something look like a dungeon. For example, use orange and red torch fire, or use light brown tents and paper, for the background of the notebook function. So, it is something identifiable; and can add unique design if done proper. I could keep going and list more colors, but I think you understand the point; add colors.   To conclude, the preparation part of the game could use a better look, in both presentation and vibrant colors. The fight part is fun if you like to tap a screen and see health bars go down. However, if there is one singular reason to download dungeon defense, it's the music. It's action music in retro tunes gives off a mysterious tone which will persuade you to continue. So if there's something optimistic you wanted to see going into the game, you'll end up listening to it instead.

I bought the game because of the amount of good reviews...after playing through the first 60 in game days I found myself super disappointed...I keep hoping there is going to be something new around the corner (otherwise why would everyone love it so much?), and in the end realised, this is just it, there is no more to this game than putting you finger in the screen and watch the chaotically flying around "bullets"...they call this game a tower defence game, no, that is not accurate, at all!  Basically there is no "gameplay" in this game at all, you go "defend" yourself again a few waves of enemies, sounds cool on paper, but the reality is that, there is no strategy involved at all, if you are strong enought in terms of level, you WILL beat the waves, if you are not, you WON'T, being skillful or not does not impact the outcome, as a matter of fact, you paying attention to the game or not does not even impact the outcome...  Most disappointed purchase I have ever made. Not going to be bothered with a refund, just in order to show respect to the indie developers, but I will be deleting the game now.

It's okay. The game is extremely simple and the early levels can be kind of fun and challenging, but as the game drags on its basically an afk game. By floor 200 on hard I wasn't even watching my screen any more because most characters spray in cones as wide as the dungeon anyway and the 4 partner characters would handle anything in the the tiny area outside of that cone.   Character unlocks become available waaaay after the game has entered the dull monotonous afk grind (300 floors on normal, 220ish on hard) and that's for the cheapest character. Unlocking an elemental requires some 3000+ floors and there's 5 of those, plus a character that requires some 2000 floors of Grinding in the Endless mode.   Upgrading is fun, although the bank and statue are basically worthless as the money you get from them gets horrifically out scaled by the price. (Pay 2 million gold for 10k a day? Gee, thanks!)  Overall, it was a good time waster for a while, but it expects you to be really really REALLY dedicated to get anything fun or interesting and I'm not willing to afk grind for literally hundreds of hours to get access to a character that would literally just make Grinding even more automatic.

The english on some the skill descriptions and forge descriptions are a little...off. They take an extra re-read to understand them. No tutorial? I know how many people detest tutorials for simple games but this game isn't entirely simple. Im at day 21 (in game days) and i have a generally good idea of how to play. For the first few days had trouble figuring out what a couple things did. Im not a casual by any means. Ive been playing games my whole life across all platforms and ive always had no trouble immediately understanding how to play any part of a game as soon as i've been exposed to it. My advice, make a optional tutorial (a short one) and have the english tweaked (it doesn't have to be perfect). Remember, this is a mobile game. Most who play it will expect simplicity or a good tutorial. Other than that, this game has a lot of potential. Excellent game so far.

content: I'm loving the game and getting more into the details of the mechanics.  Most of it is easy enough to figure out, though not explained, but there are a few things here and there that are tricky.  What does the percentage next to the weapon name actually indicate?  How things are calculated.  Translation is definitely a need which I know dev has promised by end of this month.  But I really hope that there is more clarity put in as well.  I love the direction you are taking this, keep it up!
replyContent:
First, I'm sorry I did not have enough explanation in the game. Percentage indicated on the weapon means performance (damage) per level. The higher the percentage, the higher the weapon's damage. If you are looking for items to enhance in the future, it is a good idea to choose a weapon with a high percentile.
Thank you for playing. :)
